article.description:
A visit to the Rose Garden wasn't 
good for the Golden State Warriors' playoff hopes.
article.headline: Anderson leads Portland with 21 points, seven assists
article.linkText: Blazers seem to be back on track against Warriors
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- While the Portland Trail Blazers still must wait to officially clinch a playoff spot, at least they've rebounded from a brief but worrisome slump. Derek Anderson had 21 points and seven assists as the Blazers turned in their second straight decisive victory with a 100-86 win over the Golden State Warriors on Tuesday night. Portland, trying to hold off the Minnesota Timberwolves for fourth place in the Western Conference and home-court advantage in the playoffs, was coming off a confident 112-95 thumping of the Dallas Mavericks on Friday which snapped a three-game losing streak. "We can't worry about the standings anymore. We just have to finish our games," Anderson said. "The rest will take care of itself." Anderson's 15-foot jumper put the Blazers on top 88-66 with 9:51 to play for their widest margin of the game. "Each time you win -- and that Dallas win was big for us -- you get a little more confidence for the next game,'' Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "We've got nine games left and we need to continue to play this way." Once again, however, the Blazers' success was overshadowed by off-court problems. On Monday, forward Rasheed Wallace appeared in a Washington state court to settle misdemeanor marijuana charges -- two days after rookie forward Qyntel Woods was cited for marijuana possession being stopped for speeding. On the court, the Blazers have been hampered by Scottie Pippen's knee injury, which landed him on the injured list after arthroscopic surgery on March 19. Pippen, the indisputable leader of the team, is not supposed to return until April 9 against San Antonio. "We can't wait to get him back," Anderson said, "but everyone is doing what they're capable of doing and we're still winning." The Blazers had defeated the Warriors 10 straight times at the Rose Garden since 1998, and Tuesday was no different. The Warriors took an early lead, going up 30-25 on Jason Richardson's alley-oop dunk. But the Blazers began making a move in the second quarter after Ruben Patterson's layup put Portland ahead 39-38. The Trail Blazers went ahead for good when Zach Randolph's layup made it 45-44, and Patterson's putback at the buzzer gave Portland a 55-46 lead at the break. Portland opened the second half with an 11-0 run to take a 66-46 lead. "We didn't quit when it was out of reach," Golden State coach Eric Musselman said. "But we probably didn't earn their respect like we have a lot of teams in this league." Troy Murphy led the Warriors with 22 points and 10 rebounds. Golden State dropped to 11th in the conference, 3½ games behind eighth-place Phoenix in the Western playoff race. The Warriors were still holding out slim hopes for the final playoff spot. "We're gonna have to go 6-and-1 to even have a chance, but it still depends on what the other teams do, too," guard Gilbert Arenas said. "It's going to take a miracle, but we have pulled off six in a row before." Game notes
In the first meeting this season between the two teams, a postgame scuffle broke out _ resulting in suspensions for Wells and Golden State's Chris Mills, and a fine for Wallace. ... Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp watched the game from a courtside seat. ... Woods came into the game with 1:07 left. He did not score.
